ined themselves as part of a global community. They also entered the world of politics through the creation of the Socialist Party, which became an electoral force in the first half of the twentieth century. Meléndez-Badillo shows how these workers produced, negotiated, and deployed powerful discourses that eventually shaped Puerto Rico's national mythology. By following these ragtag intellectuals as they became politicians and statesmen, Meléndez-Badillo also demonstrates how they engaged in racial and gender silencing, epistemic violence, and historical erasures in the fringes of society. Ultimately, The Lettered Barriada is about the politics of knowledge production and the tensions between working-class intellectuals and the state.Duke University Press Scholars of Color First Book Award recipient  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aIntellectualszPuerto RicoxAttitudes. 0aLabor movementzPuerto RicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aPress and politicszPuerto RicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aPress, LaborzPuerto RicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorking classxPolitical activityzPuerto RicoxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478022091zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478022091423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478022091/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles